AGENTIC-VT 1.0

[metadata]
title: 4 rivals.
1 player.: The biggest open-source web video players just merged instead of fighting.
channel: @octopusinc_
source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R9_33r1coZ8
upload_date: 20260622
transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Four of the biggest open-source video players on the web just stopped competing and merged into one project. So, here is the backstory. Video.js is probably the most used open-source video player on the web. It is embedded on'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Amazon, LinkedIn, Instagram, and Dropbox. It gets played billions of times a month, and it still pulls close to 4 million installs every month on npm. Steve Heffernan built it 16 years'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ago, back when the whole job was dragging the web off Flash and onto native HTML5 video. Now, he is back leading the project, and instead of fighting the rival players that grew up'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'around his, he got their creators to fold Plyr, Vidstack, and MediaChrome into one ground-up rewrite called Video.js version 10. Together, those projects carry around 75,000 GitHub'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stars. It is still Apache licensed, and the default player is a dramatic 88% smaller than the one it replaces. Enjoying this so far? Subscribe to the'

[01:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'YouTube channel and grab the free daily newsletter at indiehacker.news. New deep dive every weekday. The announcement itself is worth reading top to bottom. Right at the top,'

[01:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Heffernan frames the whole bet. The web he originally designed for is basically gone, so the player had to change with it. Scroll down a bit, and you hit the part everyone latched onto, a bundle size table putting the old player next'

[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the new one, and the gap is almost embarrassing. Keep going, and it gets into streaming, where the new engine does adaptive playback at a tiny fraction of what the old stack cost. Then it explains the convergence, the'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reasoning for why a pile of separate efforts was worse than one shared one. Further down, you get the new skins designed so the default player looks good straight out of the box. And right near the bottom is my favorite touch, a'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'long thank you section to every contributor, the kind of thing you only write when a project genuinely belongs to a community again. Now, to get why this is a big deal, you have to know the landscape it\'s'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collapsing. For years, if you wanted to put video on a site, you picked a lane. There was Video.js itself, the old workhorse that did everything but had grown heavy with age. There was Player,'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which people reached for when they wanted something clean without much effort. There was Vidstack, the newer, more component-driven take aimed squarely at React developers. And underneath a lot of them sat'

[02:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'MediaChrome, a low-level set of building blocks from the team at Mux. On paper, these were competitors. They solved the same problem four slightly different ways, and every one of them carried its own maintenance burden. Version 10 is'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the truce. Each of those creators is now building one player together instead of four apart. And step back for a second, because the scale here is wild. This thing started 16 years ago. It now runs on millions of'

[02:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sites. It gets played constantly around the clock, and four separate projects just collapsed into this single one. Okay. So, the headline number, the one that got this trending, is the size.'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Old Video.js shipped with adaptive streaming baked in by default, so the player most people actually loaded was heavy, well over 200 kilobytes of compressed code before a single frame of'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video. Version 10 splits that streaming back out, and its default video player lands around 25 kilobytes compressed. That is the 88% cut everyone is quoting. Put the raw players side by side, and it'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is just a stark. The old core was about 260 kilobytes minified, where the new one is around 97, and only 62 on the React build, and it keeps going down from there. A muted background video'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looping behind a hero section is about 10 kilobytes and a truly minimal React player, just a video and a play button, comes in under 5 kilobytes. Want to be featured? Pitch your'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open-source repo at indiehacker.news/apply and get in front of thousands of builders. So, how is it that much smaller without just throwing features away? The trick is that the old player handed you one'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'big do-everything bundle and version 10 flips that. You only ship the pieces you actually use. It comes with a few ready-made presets out of the box, one tuned for regular website video, one for'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audio and podcasts, and one for those silent background videos. But, the deeper change is that every part of the player is now a real separate component that you fully own. The buttons, the'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'progress bar, the menus, they are all just normal elements you can restyle or rip out. The old version made you fight its built-in styling with CSS overrides and hacks, and this one ships unstyled'

[04:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on purpose, the way modern component libraries do. So, you start from a clean slate and make it match your product. It works as plain web components in any framework or as proper React components,'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it is fully typed, so your editor actually helps you as you build. Underneath, the architecture is the actual story. The whole thing is built on top of Media Chrome, that low-level'

[05:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'web components layer from Mux. So, the new video.js is really a polished, opinionated player sitting on a shared foundation. They split the player into three clean layers, the media itself,'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the state that tracks what is happening, and the UI you see. And each one can be swapped without touching the others. State runs through a small modern store and features are literally just modules'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you import. It is written end-to-end in TypeScript. It plays nicely with Tailwind and the team building it is kind of a who\'s who, the creators of Plyr, Vidstack, and MediaChrome, plus engineers who have shipped video at'

[05:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'places like Netflix and NBC. Getting started looks about like you would expect for a modern package. You install the React build, you import the player along with the specific features you want, and you create a player by'

[06:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'handing it just those features, nothing more. Drop the component into your app, point it at a video file, and that is a working player. The whole mental model flips. You are assembling exactly the player you need'

[06:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'instead of deleting the parts of a giant one you don\'t. Now, a fair warning, this is a beta and it is worth being precise about what that means. The beta that just dropped ships those three core presets plus'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'brand new default skins designed by Sam Potts, the same person behind Plyr. So, it looks polished instead of generic. And there is one forward-looking piece I have not really seen other players'

[06:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bother with. They built it to be readable by AI coding agents. There is a machine-readable docs file. The docs come in plain markdown and there are pre-built skills sitting in the repo all so that when you ask an assistant to'

[07:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'build you a player, it generates code that actually works. The road map is public, too. It went from a technical preview late last year to this beta with a stable release aimed at the middle of'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this year and full feature parity with the old video.js targeted by the end of it. So, should you actually use this today? Be honest with yourself about the stage it is at. The APIs are still moving, so'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anything you build right now might need tweaks before the stable release. A lot of the heavier features people rely on are still being ported over, which means for a big production site, the old'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version is still the safe pick for a little while longer. But if you are starting something fresh, or you have ever cursed at a video player for being a bloated, impossible to style black box, this is the most'

[07:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exciting thing to happen in this corner of the web in years. The bigger story might honestly be the precedent. A bunch of rival maintainers looked at all the duplicated effort, swallowed their egos,'

[08:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and decided that users were better served by one great thing than four good ones. If that idea catches on anywhere else, we all win. Everything is linked below if you want to follow along.'
